title: National Register of Historic Places listings in Pine County, Minnesota
data: Church built 1914-15 to anchor the Danish American community of Askov , Pine County 's most significant ethnic enclave
Highly intact one-room school built in 1899 and expanded in 1909 , representing the typical venue for education in rural Pine County in the first half of the 20th century
Off County Highway 43 46°18′32″N 92°46′12″W / 46.309007°N 92.769966°W / 46.309007 ; -92.769966 ( John Doboszenski Farmstead )
One of the few surviving examples of Pine County 's early subsistence farmsteads , established in 1894 . Also associated with the initial settlement of the area by Polish immigrants
Rare intact example of the emergency housing built for survivors of the Great Hinckley Fire in 1894 , symbolizing one of Minnesota 's worst wildfires and the state 's humanitarian aid response
Minnesota Highway 48 46°00′46″N 92°27′00″W / 46.012703°N 92.450014°W / 46.012703 ; -92.450014 ( Hinckley State Line Marker )
State entrance sign built 1941-42 , encapsulating NPS rustic style and the early roadside developments produced by the Minnesota highway department in partnership with New Deal agencies
Louis Hultgren House and Sand Pit
Minnesota Highway 23 46°20′21″N 92°35′25″W / 46.339167°N 92.590278°W / 46.339167 ; -92.590278 ( Louis Hultgren House and Sand Pit )
Circa-1896 house and adjacent molding sand quarry of a Swedish immigrant , associated with an early Pine County industry and the founding of Kerrick
Minnesota Highway 123 over the Kettle River 46°07′44″N 92°51′24″W / 46.128874°N 92.856577°W / 46.128874 ; -92.856577 ( Kettle River Bridge )
Rare Minnesota example of a deck truss bridge , built 1947-48 , and further distinguished by unusual cantilevering and hinging features to accommodate a challenging site
Old Wagon Rd . 46°07′58″N 92°51′28″W / 46.132901°N 92.857666°W / 46.132901 ; -92.857666 ( Kettle River Sandstone Company Quarry )
Minnesota 's largest late-19th/early-20th-century sandstone quarry , active 1885-1919 ; the source of local prosperity and an internationally used building material . Now Robinson Park
1913 farm noted for its distinctive bungalow house and stone-faced barn and silo , as well as its association with a prominent local building contractor
Main and 4th Sts . 46°07′56″N 92°52′00″W / 46.132148°N 92.866686°W / 46.132148 ; -92.866686 ( Minneapolis Trust Company Commercial Building )

1894 commercial building connected with the efforts of James J. Hill and his son-in-law Samuel Hill to swiftly rebuild Sandstone after the Great Hinckley Fire . Now the Sandstone History and Art Center
1804 fur trading post reconstructed on its original site by the Minnesota Historical Society . Now the Snake River Fur Post
Front St. at Finland Ave. 46°12′02″N 92°54′58″W / 46.200593°N 92.916041°W / 46.200593 ; -92.916041 ( Northern Pacific Depot )
Pine County 's best surviving example of its small-town train stations - built in 1909 - and representative of the essential role of the railways in its settlement

Railway station built in 1895 as a duplicate of the original lost in the Great Hinckley Fire , symbolizing the destruction of that event and the seminal state conservation program that it spurred . Now the Hinckley Fire Museum
One of the area 's most fashionable houses , built circa 1896 for a leading local entrepreneur
1901 example of the simple , one-room public buildings erected in early Pine County settlements , and a witness to Askov 's evolution from a railroad stop to a Danish American colony
Red Clover Land Company Demonstration Farm
Off County Road 32 46°10′14″N 92°21′02″W / 46.170647°N 92.350426°W / 46.170647 ; -92.350426 ( Red Clover Land Company Demonstration Farm )
Showplace farmstead built circa 1915 by the company instrumental in attracting settlers to eastern Pine County , but whose easy terms prompted many to default and leave within a decade
30065 St. Croix Park Rd . 45°57′03″N 92°34′12″W / 45.950717°N 92.570128°W / 45.950717 ; -92.570128 ( St. Croix Recreational Demonstration Area )

Recreational Demonstration Area developed 1934-43 , a major New Deal undertaking noted for its landscape architecture , social impact , and the state 's largest collection of NPS Rustic park facilities ( 164 contributing properties ) . Now St. Croix State Park
Commercial Ave. between 5th and 6th Sts . 46°07′58″N 92°51′50″W / 46.132715°N 92.863854°W / 46.132715 ; -92.863854 ( Sandstone School )
Sandstone school whose oldest sections date to 1901 and 1910 ; an exceptional product of local stonecutting and masonry expertise
Arnold Schwyzer Summer House and Farmstead
County Road 17 46°07′12″N 93°00′07″W / 46.119957°N 93.001907°W / 46.119957 ; -93.001907 ( Arnold Schwyzer Summer House and Farmstead )
Summer home and hobby farm developed 1902-1920s , example of the private lake retreats built in Pine County by affluent urbanites . Now the Audubon Center of the North Woods
Linear and conical mounds dating to c. 600 CE

intro: This is a list of the National Register of Historic Places listings in Pine County, Minnesota. It is intended to be a complete list of the properties and districts on the National Register of Historic Places in Pine County, Minnesota, United States. The locations of National Register properties and districts for which the latitude and longitude coordinates are included below, may be seen in an online map. There are 21 properties and districts listed on the National Register in the county, including a National Historic Landmark district. A supplementary list includes three additional sites that were formerly on the National Register.
